     Go Project Folder Structure — CLI + WebServer UI

     Context

     The workforceDbSchema project already has a complete PostgreSQL schema: Goose migrations (sql/migrations/), sqlc query files
     (sql/queries/), and generated Go code (internal/db/). The next step is to add Go application code: a CLI tool (import runner, admin
     ops, month rollover) and a WebServer (REST API + WebUI table). No go.mod exists yet — this is a greenfield Go module on top of a
     finished schema.

     ---
     Recommended Directory Layout

     workforceDbSchema/
     ├── go.mod                          # module: github.com/<you>/workforce-planning
     ├── go.sum
     ├── Makefile                        # build, run, migrate, generate shortcuts
     │
     ├── cmd/
     │   ├── cli/
     │   │   └── main.go                 # CLI entry point (Cobra root + subcommands)
     │   └── server/
     │       └── main.go                 # HTTP server entry point
     │
     ├── internal/
     │   ├── db/                         # ← existing, sqlc-generated (do not edit)
     │   ├── config/
     │   │   └── config.go               # env vars + Config struct (DATABASE_URL, PORT, …)
     │   ├── service/
     │   │   ├── actuals.go              # SAP import, CopyFrom bulk insert
     │   │   ├── forecast.go             # SCD write pair, version lifecycle, rollover
     │   │   └── reporting.go            # monthly rollup, version diff
     │   ├── api/
     │   │   ├── handler/
     │   │   │   ├── forecast.go         # HTTP handlers — forecast CRUD
     │   │   │   ├── actuals.go          # HTTP handlers — import & actuals read
     │   │   │   └── costcenter.go       # HTTP handlers — CC hierarchy
     │   │   ├── middleware/
     │   │   │   ├── auth.go             # JWT / session check
     │   │   │   └── logger.go           # structured request logging
     │   │   └── router.go               # chi router wiring
     │   └── cli/
     │       ├── import.go               # "wfp import <file>" subcommand
     │       ├── rollover.go             # "wfp rollover" subcommand
     │       └── version.go              # "wfp version list/archive" subcommands
     │
     ├── web/                            # frontend static assets (optional)
     │   └── dist/                       # compiled JS/CSS (gitignored, built by npm)
     │
     ├── sql/                            # ← existing
     │   ├── migrations/
     │   └── queries/
     │
     └── docs/                           # ← existing
         └── sqlc-usage.md

     ---
     Key Decisions

     Module name

     github.com/<your-github-user>/workforce-planning
     Use a real or placeholder GitHub path — Go tooling requires a valid module path.

     CLI framework: Cobra

     - cmd/cli/main.go creates the Cobra root command and calls Execute().
     - Each subcommand (import, rollover, version) lives in internal/cli/ so it can be tested without invoking main.
     - Cobra handles --help, flag parsing, and nested subcommand routing without boilerplate.

     HTTP router: chi

     - Lightweight, uses standard http.Handler, and supports middleware chaining cleanly.
     - If the UI is a SPA (React/HTMX), web/dist/ is embedded into the binary with //go:embed web/dist in cmd/server/main.go.
     - If the UI is server-side HTML templates, add internal/api/templates/ with html/template files.

     Service layer (internal/service/)

     - Sits between HTTP handlers / CLI commands and internal/db/.
     - Holds all business logic: the SCD two-step write pair, month rollover (archive + seed), bulk CopyFrom import.
     - Takes db.Querier (the sqlc-generated interface) as a dependency → easy to mock in tests.
     - Wraps multi-step operations in a transaction using the WithTx pattern from docs/sqlc-usage.md.

     Config (internal/config/)

     - Single Config struct loaded from environment variables (os.Getenv or godotenv for .env files).
     - Required fields: DATABASE_URL, PORT (server). Optional: LOG_LEVEL, JWT_SECRET.
     - Both cmd/cli/main.go and cmd/server/main.go call config.Load() at startup before connecting to the DB.

     Audit session variable placement

     - SET LOCAL app.current_user_id = $1 belongs inside each service-layer transaction, not in HTTP middleware — so that CLI commands
     also set it correctly for the audit trigger.

